## Syntax Breakdown

```dart
try {
  int age = int.parse('hello');
  print('This will never print'); // Skipped!
} catch (e) {
  print('Oops! Something broke. Sending user a warning...');
  print('The actual error was: $e');
}
```
The `(e)` holds the actual Exception object that was thrown, so you can inspect *why* it crashed.

## On Clause

Sometimes an operation can fail in three different ways (No WiFi, Bad Password, Server Down).
You can stack `on` blocks before the `catch` to handle specific exceptions differently!

```dart
try {
  // Dangerous code
} on FormatException {
  print('You typed letters instead of numbers!');
} on TimeoutException {
  print('Your internet is too slow!');
} catch (e) {
  print('Some totally unknown error occurred: $e');
}
```

